In order to demonstrate the sensitivity of this system, TA standard solution in different concentrations were mixed with the NCDs and the fluorescence intensity was measured under the optimized conditions. As displayed in Fig. 6A, the fluorescence intensity of NCDs was gradually decreased with increasing TA concentration. Meanwhile, it was clear that the decreased fluorescence showed good linear response to the TA concentration in the range of 0.4–9.0 μmol L−1, the calibration curve (Fig. 6B) can be express as ∆F = 544.68c + 10.12, R

                           2
                         = 0.9990, where ∆F (F
                        0 − F) is the difference between the fluorescence intensity in the absence of TA (F

                           0
                        ) and in its presence (F), and c is concentration of TA. The limit detection (3σ/k) for TA is 0.12 μmol L−1, where σ represents the standard deviation of blank measurements, and s is the slope of the calibration curve. Our method provided a better detection limit than most other reported analytical methods for TA (shown in Table 1
                        ). Interestingly, the absorption spectrum increased after TA was mixed with NCDs as shown in Fig. 6C, which may be attributed to ground state interaction. Fig. 6D illustrated a linear effect toward TA in the concentration range of 0.8–4.8 μmol L−1 with a correlation coefficient (R

                           2
                        ) of 0.9954. The detection limit is determined to be 0.24 μmol L−1.
